1101455349163483137.text: This was incredible to hear from the many self proclaimed bitcoin maximalists at the event. Everyone is recognizing that the trolling and vitriol online does not help our industry grow at all. When we meet in person, we tend to be less mean than many online personas.

1101454676036329473.text: I learned that the Monero community is doing some amazing  stuff organizing their communities as well. Side note about @tabconf - a constant theme throughout the entire event was an emphasis on getting people to meet up at physical events.

1101453929236365314.text: When I was at @tabconf, I hung out with several Monero community members through the weekend, and never learned any of their real names. If someone cares about opsec and privacy, they can choose to stay pseudonymous. It will get easier as the industry grows.

1101453170709094400.text: Hackathons combined as city councils or other governance functions can help keep people accountable for various reputation-based cryptoeconomic systems.  When conferences are large enough there is no need for a person to use their real name if they choose not to.

1101452707590750208.text: This is messy and not defined anywhere as “official governance” for Ethereum, but sets a standard for other protocols and digital jurisdictions to learn from. The key piece here is that it is truly human-centered, using technology to bring us together.

1101452310016901121.text: Inspired individuals create rings through @EthMagicians - giving opportunities for anyone to prove themselves and act as an informal representative for the now many interests in the Ethereum digital jurisdiction that everyone participating *chooses* to be a part of.

1101451984597594112.text: @ETHGlobal events are an amazing phenomenon and are becoming a piece of Ethereum’s off-chain governance. Leaders of the community recognized through meritocratic means fly all around the world to mentor and help new entrants build on the platform.

1101451574063316994.text: How do we combat this? As an industry we need to continue designing events that bring participants of protocols together - this builds trust and acts as an anti-sybil mechanism. We’re already seeing it in the Ethereum community.

1044595060514467848.text: There is space for many competitors in the same vertical, and with only two having reached any prominence, we are just getting started with crypto changing the world.

1044594856918753280.text: With all that said, the only crypto networks that have gained any traction and usage are bitcoin and Ethereum. In 2014 it was a new “bitcoin killer” every other week. Now we are seeing the latest “Ethereum killers” come online.

1044594638777192448.text:
I see a future where hundreds of verticals (instead of 7) in this stack exist with many competing versions of the same protocol compete to gain usage. 

In an open source world, technical advancements are commoditized, which give communities and governance more weight in success.

1044593960214302721.text:
A key difference in this future is that each protocol is more like a public good, where it is easy to participate, and owned primarily by the people who use the token. 

People vote with their tokens, and if they choose not to participate, they can sell and move on.

1044593869269151744.text: We’re seeing this happen in the Ethereum network today. Every new non-fungible token, DEX and stable coin increases the utility of the network as a whole and the potential for other DApps to succeed.

1044593167281123329.text:
A great metaphor for all these protocols being built are sovereign nations. True digital jurisdiction is being created with these crypto networks. 

The crypto landscape becomes closer to what globalism is today, where protocols are increasingly interdependent on each other.

1044593001744470016.text:
As crypto networks mature, they will increasingly become interdependent. 

Developers are empowered to build on platforms that won’t pull the rug out from under them. 

This podcast by @cdixon and @fredwilson gives context into where we are in this cycle -https://overcast.fm/+BlzFPJdLY

1044591658430590976.text: While it is still early and these protocols are largely isolated from each other, I see a future where most user facing DApps depend on several of these verticals, exactly how our largest companies depend on the core internet protocols today.

1044591507309842433.text:
Each vertical has many competing protocols within. Many are built as “applications” on top of smart contract platforms or are their own separate blockchain. 

What matters is that there is a protocol that allows for permissionless building and shared success.

1044590924859396096.text: We have an increasing number of defined core protocol verticals since the creation of bitcoin in 2009. This includes digital gold, general smart contract platforms, anonymous money, identity, file storage, prediction markets.. and the list keeps growing.

1044590766356647936.text: Most value is accrued by companies built on top of these core protocols. See @joelmonegro’s Fat Protocol post from 2016. Though out of date (things move fast in crypto land), it provides context for where value will move in a future where blockchains win - http://www.usv.com/blog/fat-protocols …

1044590447853797376.text: Outside of having a .com domain, there isn’t much value accrued to each protocol despite how much of the modern economy is built upon them.

1044590352303378433.text: Each layer has dozens of protocols that contribute to the success of moving information in between each layer - some more critical than others. This includes http, https, tcp/ip, smtp, ftp, dns, etc.

1044590189119787009.text:
We're still in the first inning of blockchains and crypto networks. 

Using the internet as a corollary, the OSI model separates how the internet works into 7 conceptual layers.
